{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413545"},"attributes":{"position":21,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T08:16:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T08:16:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15180"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534812"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:50:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:50:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15180"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"15180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15180"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.23,0.6,0.06,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7871"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105631"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7871"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15180"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88077"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"107"},{"type":"tags","id":"278"},{"type":"tags","id":"306"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"1157"},{"type":"tags","id":"2249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2253"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"2564"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"5967"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38571"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105631"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe junior doctor covering the general medical ward overnight is urgently paged to review a patient with new hypoxia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man has been admitted to hospital with recurrent right great toe osteomyelitis. He has a medical history of obesity with a BMI of 42 kg/m2, obstructive sleep apnoea, poorly controlled type 2 diabetes, hypertension, congestive heart failure, and chronic lymphoedema. His regular medications include amlodipine, metformin, and furosemide. He was also administered paracetamol and oxycodone one hour ago for pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears drowsy but rousable to voice. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He is noted to have loud snoring with periods of apnoea. His chest is clear on auscultation. His lower limbs are enlarged and show chronic lymphoedematous changes. There is cellulitis and a deep ulcer overlying his right great toe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst awaiting assistance, an arterial blood gas is taken and shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.32 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2 52 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpO2 58 mmHg (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3 26 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his hypoxia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sepsis","Opiate toxicity","Obstructive sleep apnoea","Pulmonary embolism","Acute pulmonary oedema"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with hypoxia and hypercapnia in the context of known obstructive sleep apnoea (OSA), recent opiate administration, and clinical features consistent with upper airway obstruction. The combination of these factors strongly suggests\u003Cstrong\u003E obstructive sleep apnoea\u003C/strong\u003E as the cause of his hypoxia. The arterial blood gas shows type 2 respiratory failure with respiratory acidosis, which is consistent with OSA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpiate toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E can cause respiratory depression and contribute to worsening OSA, but the patient remains rousable and his respiratory rate is not severely depressed, making pure opiate toxicity and hypoventilation less likely as the primary cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with tachypnoea, tachycardia and type 1 respiratory failure which are not present here. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESepsis\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with fever, tachycardia, and other signs of systemic inflammatory response. While the patient has cellulitis, his vital signs are relatively stable and do not suggest sepsis as the cause of his hypoxia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pulmonary oedema\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with orthopnoea, bilateral crackles on chest auscultation, and often peripheral oedema. While the patient has a history of chronic heart failure, the clear chest examination and characteristic sleep-disordered breathing pattern make acute pulmonary oedema less likely as the primary cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management should focus on reducing opiate doses if possible, positioning the patient appropriately (usually semi-upright or lateral), and considering the use of CPAP. Regular SpO2 monitoring is essential, and if the patient uses CPAP at home, this should be continued during the admission.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Obstructive sleep apnoea is commonly exacerbated during acute illness, particularly when patients are supine.","Type 2 respiratory failure in OSA patients may worsen with opiate use and decreased consciousness.","Early recognition and appropriate positioning/oxygen therapy can prevent further deterioration in OSA patients."],"references":["Mirabile VS, Shebl E, Sankari A, et al. Respiratory Failure in Adults. [Updated 2023 Jun 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526127/","Bhutta BS, Alghoula F, Berim I. Hypoxia. [Updated 2024 Mar 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482316/","Martinez-Garcia MA, S\u00e1nchez-de-la-Torre M, White DP, Azarbarzin A. Hypoxic Burden in Obstructive Sleep Apnea: Present and Future. Archivos de Bronconeumolog\u00eda. 2023;59(1):36-43. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0300289622005129"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88077"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15180"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88077"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-11T09:42:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-11T09:42:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7871"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105631"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.eme